        <p data-uuid="dcc5d067fe0b4181a7579869acadc603">Many older Americans considered this behavior scandalous. However, one 1920s writer expressed her admiration for flappers, saying about her young daughter:</p>
        <section class="pullquote_wrapper" data-uuid="3d7b4ac58c014c78a4d30fd4aa14d12e">
            <p class="pullquote hang" data-uuid="31bca162fc2a4991aca00ff336456e2d">“I want my girl to do what she pleases, be what she pleases. . . . I want her to be a flapper, because flappers are brave.”</p>
            <div class="pullquote_attribution_wrapper" data-uuid="211c60aff786422e895dacd7ef0f389a">
                <p class="pullquote_address" data-uuid="8fa4f8500f014c90a09199b5882d9ed4">—Zelda Fitzgerald,<br />
                </p>
                <p class="p_source" data-uuid="4dd753f7ccd247c8ac02acff7b3db951">quoted in <i>Zelda</i>, by Nancy Mitford</p>
            </div>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="810e77cc4cdc4f12bf6a3f4211ba342c">Fashion magazines, Hollywood movies, and advertising helped promote this new images and ideas of youthful freedom.<br />
        </p>
